  "text": "As thermoneutral housing accelerated the onset of metabolic inflammation during obesity 65 , two studies that were published in 2016 asked whether thermoneutral housing might potentiate vascular inflammation and atherosclerosis [CITATION_1] 72 . Using Apoe -/-mice, thermoneutral housing was found to enhance the development of atherogenic lesions in the aortas of mice that were fed a Western diet 65 . This increase in atherogenesis was associated with inflammatory changes in and around the vessel wall, as demonstrated by increased infiltration of the vessel wall and perivascular fat by inflammatory macrophages and dendritic cells. A similar increase in lesion area was observed in another study, which found that Apoe −/− mice housed at thermoneutrality had larger atherosclerotic lesions in their aortic roots than mice housed at 22 °C (REF. 72 ). These investigators also tested whether thermoneutral housing could induce atherogenesis in C57BL/6J mice, which are usually resistant to the development of atherosclerosis. Although the lesions were smaller, C57BL/6J mice housed at an ambient temperature of 30 °C showed evidence of inflammatory atherogenic lesions in their aortic roots, which was not observed in mice housed at an ambient temperature of 23 °C. Moreover, C57BL/6J mice that were fed a Western diet at thermoneutrality developed hypercholesterolaemia with a substantial proportion of their total cholesterol in LDL, a lipoprotein profile that is similar to that of humans. Importantly, in these two studies, the increased propensity of mice to develop atherogenic plaques at ambient temperatures of 30 °C occurred despite improvements in haemodynamic parameters (heart rate and blood pressure), which suggests that thermoneutral housing of Apoe -/-mice might be a useful preclinical model for testing the efficacy of anti-inflammatory therapies.",
